# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: skinner-reserve
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The **1877 VFA season** was the inaugural season of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), the highest-level Australian rules football competition in the colony of Victoria.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] It was the first season in which football in Victoria was run under a properly constituted administrative body.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The VFA was formed with the view to governing the sport via a collective body, made up of delegates representing the clubs.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Although the formation was a significant step in the organisation of football, it was effectively an administrative change only, and there was no significant change to the manner in which matches were scheduled and played – or the premiership decided – compared to the unaffiliated 1876 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Carlton won the inaugural VFA premiership after finishing the season with 14 wins from its 21 matches.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The Victorian Football Association was established on 17 May 1877 to provide administration of the game in Victoria.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] It was the second such body to have been formed, after the South Australian Football Association (SAFA) was formed 17 days prior to the VFA.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Prior to 1877, the laws of the game had been agreed to at an annual meeting of club secretaries, however the clubs remained entirely independent and unaffiliated.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] This meant that when a dispute existed between two clubs, there was no formal means of resolving it or enforcing a decision.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Additionally, the matter of whether or not Albert Park won the Challenge Cup in 1870 was never formally resolved.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The new Association was established, and was modelled in large part on the Victorian Cricket Association (VCA), which had been established in September 1875 to provide a similar level of centralised administration over Victorian cricket.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The Victorian Football Association comprised one delegate from each senior metropolitan club (and from senior country clubs by proxy) and a vote of those club delegates could make a decision which was binding on any associated club.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Junior clubs were also managed by the Association, but did not have representation on the board.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The Association comprised a range of senior and junior clubs from Melbourne and around the colony of Victoria.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] There were five inaugural metropolitan senior clubs: Albert Park, Carlton, Hotham, Melbourne and St Kilda.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Provincial senior teams included Ballarat, Ballarat Albion, Barwon Geelong, Kyneton and Sandhurst.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] There was also a wide range of affiliated junior clubs, including Brunswick, Clifton, Coburg, Essendon, Excelsior, Hotham United, Sandridge, Toorak, Sandridge, South Melbourne, Victorian Railways, Warwick, West Melbourne, and Williamstown.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The 1877 premiership was won by the Carlton Football Club, which played twenty-one matches during the year, winning fourteen and drawing four.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Melbourne finished second, having played twenty-three matches, winning sixteen and drawing four.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] At the time, Melbourne and Carlton were considered to be by far the strongest senior clubs, so Carlton's position as the top club was based almost entirely on head-to-head matches between the two clubs – of which Carlton won two, Melbourne won one, and one was drawn.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The below table is set of results for the 1877 season, showing the records of the five senior metropolitan clubs.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The list shows the record across all matches, including senior, junior and intercolonial matches.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The clubs are listed in the order in which they were ranked in *The Australasian*.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] In the provincial competition, Barwon was the strongest team, while Geelong was second.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] The below shows the record of provincial clubs against senior metropolitan clubs.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] In the junior competition, West Melbourne was the strongest club, going undefeated against junior clubs with its sole loss coming against senior club Melbourne.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Essendon was second, with five wins and six draws from its 17 games.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Both clubs were admitted into the VFA's senior ranks for the following season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1877-vfa-season] Toorak was undefeated in all its matches.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The **1965 VFA season** was the 84th season of the top division of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), and the fifth season of second division competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Division 2 premiership was won by Preston; it was the club's second Division 2 premiership in three years, having competed in and been relegated from Division 1 in the intervening year.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] In the early 1960s, several Victorian Football League clubs were interested in leaving their traditional home grounds, and many were looking at Association grounds as possible new homes.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The move was a success for St Kilda, but resulted in Moorabbin being suspended from the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] On 25 June 1964, three months after St Kilda's move to Moorabbin was first announced, it was revealed that the Coburg Council had approached the North Melbourne Football Club, and that they were discussing terms for the club to relocate its operations to Coburg Oval on a long-term lease.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The ground was one of the best in the Association at the time, and the Coburg Council had ambitions of seeing League football played on it.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The loss of its ground would have meant expulsion from the Association, so from the time the move was first announced, the Coburg Football Club was staunchly opposed to the council's actions, and vowed to fight the move.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Coburg examined a number of legal options, and appealed unsuccessfully to force a referendum of ratepayers.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] In November 1964, the council and club began working on terms for a 40-year lease, under which the council would spend £80,000 to bring the venue to League standards, and North Melbourne would serve as ground manager, pay £4,000 per year in rent, and £50,000 for upgrades over thirty years.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The council gave its formal approval for a lease by a narrow 6–5 majority on 11 January 1965, and North Melbourne took occupancy on a week-to-week basis from 1 February, while the lease was finalized.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Over the following months, the terms of the lease were renegotiated, and when the lease was formally signed on 2 April 1965, it was for a term of only seven years, much shorter than the forty-year terms which had initially been discussed.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The League itself leased the North Melbourne Cricket Ground for £1,500 during 1965, and used it junior football, umpire training, school programs, and from June it was used as a central ground for the Essendon District Football League game-of-the-week.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] By December 1964, it looked unlikely that Coburg would be able to continue in the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Because of the bleak outlook, the club began to discuss the possibility of amalgamating with North Melbourne – a move which the Association warned would likely result in its suspension, as had occurred to Moorabbin eight months earlier.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] On 8 December, Coburg and North Melbourne agreed to terms for an amalgamation.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] One week later, North Melbourne agreed to amend its constitution to facilitate the amalgamation.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Fourteen Coburg committeemen transferred to North Melbourne over the following months, and all were suspended from the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Coburg committee had been divided on the decision to amalgamate with North Melbourne, and on 17 December, the Association executive helped to facilitate the formation of a new Coburg committee from ten committeemen and fourteen life members who were opposed to the amalgamation.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The new committee and the Association both refused to recognise the amalgamation, and worked to keep Coburg in the Association for the 1965 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] It was unclear in December whether or not they would succeed in fielding a team, and the Association did not include Coburg in its initial 1965 fixture, released on 18 December; but, by February the club and the Association had confirmed that Coburg would field a team in 1965.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] In March, arrangements were made for Coburg to share North Port Oval with Port Melbourne for senior games during 1965, with the seconds to play at Lagoon Reserve, Port Melbourne.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Through the season, there was a political struggle between the two Coburg committees, each rejecting the other's legitimacy, and the office-bearers of the former committee refused to turn club documents over to the new committee.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] After discussions, both the council and the football club decided that it was in neither's best interests to continue the arrangement, and on 28 September 1965 the lease was terminated by mutual agreement after only eight months of the seven-year term.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Coburg Football Club, which had been making an effort to find a new permanent home ground and had suffered on-field and financially during its season at Port Melbourne, was able to return to Coburg Oval from the 1966 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] North Melbourne returned to the North Melbourne Cricket Ground in 1966, turning down an offer from the St Kilda Cricket Club to move to the St Kilda Cricket Ground; the terms of its new agreement with the Melbourne City Council were less favourable for the club than its previous agreement.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] In 1964, the Sunshine Council agreed to lease Sunshine's home ground, Selwyn Park, to the George Cross soccer club.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] To secure agreement from the football club to end its existing lease early, the Sunshine Council committed to developing a new Association standard venue at Skinner Reserve in Braybrook.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The venue was built during the 1965 season, with the football club signing a seven-year lease to begin from 1966.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] In July 1965, before the venue was finished, the League's Footscray Football Club made an application to the Sunshine Council to permanently move its playing and administrative base from Western Oval to Skinner Reserve, and to develop it further to a League standard venue.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] As had been the case for Coburg and Moorabbin, Sunshine's place in the Association would have been in jeopardy if Footscray had made the move; but, in September the council formally decided to honour its existing agreement with the Sunshine, and rejected Footscray's application.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Sunshine began playing at the new venue in 1966.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] While Footscray's application at Braybrook was under consideration, Yarraville made an opportunistic application to the Footscray Council to replace Footscray at the Western Oval; this was also rejected once Footscray was confirmed to be staying.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] St Kilda's and North Melbourne's moves into Association grounds damaged the relationship between the Association and the League.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] As a result of this, on 9 April, the Association Board of Management voted by 27–9 majority to cease reciprocal recognition of League clearances, opening the door for League players to cross to the Association without a clearance.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] This state of affairs existed until June 1966, when the Australian National Football Council intervened; up until this time, only Eddie Melai, who transferred from South Melbourne to Dandenong, took the opportunity.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] However, disputes over clearances began again with the Association's imposition of transfer fees from 1967, and the disputes eventually culminated in the Association's expulsion from the Australian National Football Council in 1970.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] In October 1964, the Association Board of Management voted to admit the Werribee Football Club to Division 2 of the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Werribee was a newly established senior club, formed from an amalgamation of four Werribee-based clubs which had competed in the Werribee District Football League: Werribee South, Irish National Foresters, Services and Metro Farm.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The new club played its games at Chirnside Park.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Five other clubs had applied: Boronia, Chelsea, Frankston, Keilor and Ringwood.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Association had also been in favour of admitting Frankston, but the club failed to get a clearance from the Mornington Peninsula Football League, so was unable to make the move.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Immediately prior to the season, Brighton–Caulfield changed its name to Caulfield.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The club further severed its connection with Brighton's identity by adopting a new guernsey of white with navy blue hoops, and adopting Bears as a new nickname.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Division 1 home-and-home season was played over 18 rounds; the top four then contested the finals under the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Finals were held at North Port Oval; the preliminary and Grand Finals for Division 1 were both held on Sunday for the first time; the semi-finals, which were played while Division 2 was still playing, remained on Saturdays.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) percentage; 3) number of points for.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Division 2 home-and-home season was played over 18 rounds, with each team playing 16 games and having two byes; the top four then contested the finals under the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] All finals were played on Sundays at Toorak Park.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] The Association played two interstate matches during 1965, against Western Australia in Perth and against Tasmania in Melbourne.
[src:skinner-reserve/1965-vfa-season] As in 1964, Williamstown's Gerry Callahan coached the team, and Sunshine's Shaun Crosbie was captain.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The **1987 VFA season** was the 106th season of the top division of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), and the 27th season of second division competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Division 1 premiership was won by the Springvale Football Club, after it defeated Port Melbourne in the Grand Final on 20 September by 38 points; it was Springvale's first Division 1 premiership, won in just its fourth season in the first division.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Division 2 premiership was won by Prahran; it was the club's second Division 2 premiership, and the last premiership ever won by the club in either division.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The 1987 season was tumultuous on and off the field, with three separate clubs – Moorabbin, Geelong West and Caulfield – suspended from the Association at different times during the year.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] In mid-1986, the Association organised the Football Organisation Review Team (FORT), which was tasked with reviewing the medium and long term structure of the Association and how it would fit within the wider Victorian football landscape.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The FORT was given *carte blanche* to review how best to structure the Association into the future.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The VFL was also going through dramatic changes which were altering the wider football landscape in Victoria.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] In October 1986, the League admitted newly established clubs based in Perth (the West Coast Eagles) and south-eastern Queensland (the Brisbane Bears).
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Thereafter followed wide speculation about further national expansion of the VFL, with expressions of interest from private consortiums, leagues and clubs in Adelaide, Canberra, Fremantle and Tasmania, and speculation that the struggling Victorian clubs would relocate, merge or fold.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] As such, the future composition of the League was very uncertain at the time, but it was considered realistic that within only a few years, the League could have expanded to a fully national competition, with a reduction in the number of Victorian-based clubs competing.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Map of clubs at the time of the FORT review.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Teams shown with blue dots or arrows were included in the FORT's new Division 1; teams shown with red dots were excluded.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Note: the backdrop of this map is greater Melbourne ca.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] To do this effectively, the Association would be best structured as a single division of twelve strong, viable clubs, with promotion and relegation abandoned permanently.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The FORT named its twelve clubs, based upon a number of off-field criteria including tradition, location, quality of facilities, and level of support from locals, councils and sponsors.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The twelve clubs named were: from Division 1, Box Hill, Coburg, Frankston, Geelong West, Port Melbourne, Preston, Sandringham and Williamstown; from Division 2, Dandenong, Oakleigh and Prahran; and a new club based in Ringwood.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Under the proposal, the second division would continue, but it would now be a suburban league operating under the auspices of the Victorian Metropolitan Football League, with no prospects of promotion to Division 1.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The eleven clubs who were excluded from the FORT's vision were: Division 1 clubs Brunswick and Springvale; and Division 2 clubs Berwick, Camberwell, Caulfield, Moorabbin, Mordialloc, Northcote, Sunshine, Waverley and Werribee.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The FORT sought to implement this change by 1988, but needed a three-quarters majority from a vote of the Board of Management to achieve a formal mandate, which would have required several of the excluded clubs to vote in favour of their own exclusion.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] By April 1987, Andersen recognised that he did not have enough support to get the changes through, and it was never formally put to the vote.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The FORT also recommended that the Association's Board of Management, which was the primary decision-making body within the Association, be restructured.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Since the Association's foundation, the Board had been formed from club delegates, the consequence being that the Association could pass changes only if a majority of clubs voted for them.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The FORT recommended an independent board comprising five delegates: three elected by Division 1 clubs, one elected by Division 2 clubs, and one from the VFL Commission.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] This would allow the Board to make more difficult decisions in the interest of the Association as a whole, rather than rely on clubs who could vote down changes on self-interest.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The motion for an independent board was put to the vote on 5 May 1987, and fell one vote short of the three-quarters majority it required, with 17–7 in favour.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] A second vote was held in July, with the size of the proposed board expanded to six, but it this time it was comfortably voted down by a 10–14 margin.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The independent board of management was eventually approved in March 1988.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Although the FORT's structural recommendations were never formally mandated, eight clubs left or were forced out of the Association within only 2½ years of the review, with most of those clubs placing part of the blame on the fall-out from the FORT review.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Many clubs also expressed bitterness upon their departures that they felt that the Association executive became more willing to allow weaker clubs to decline and fail without intervening, in order to allow the Association to progress naturally towards the FORT's vision.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Within only six years, the Association had contracted to the point where it almost matched the FORT's vision.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The second division was abandoned at the start of 1989, and by 1991 there were only twelve teams remaining in the Association: ten were among the twelve clubs named by the FORT, with excluded clubs Springvale and Werribee surviving in place of Geelong West and the proposed Ringwood club.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Association ended up becoming the top Victorian state-level competition following an administrative change in 1995, but it was not until 2000, a full thirteen years after the review, that the Association finally fulfilled the FORT's vision of merging with the League reserves.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Three clubs were suspended from the Association at different stages during the year: Moorabbin, Geelong West and Caulfield.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] On Thursday 23 April, three days before Round 3, Moorabbin coach Graham Stewart resigned from the club over a number of disagreements with the board.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The exact nature of the disagreements was not widely publicised, but they covered a range of areas in the management of the club and team, including player payments.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Ten senior players immediately walked out in support of Stewart.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Lacking players willing to play, the club forfeited its Round 3 games against Oakleigh in all three grades.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Association issued an ultimatum to Moorabbin that if it could not field a team in all three grades, it would be suspended from the competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Former Oakleigh premiership player Tom Quinn was appointed coach on 29 April, but the club was unable to coax enough players back, and it forfeited its Round 4 matches against Sunshine.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] As such, on 6 May, the Association executive committee suspended Moorabbin from the firsts and Seconds competitions for the remainder of the season; the rest of Moorabbin's games were treated as forfeitures.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The club ultimately never sought readmission to the competition in 1988, and folded, bringing to an end a brief tenure of just over four seasons in the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Although it was identified as one of the future Division 1 clubs under the FORT's proposal, Geelong West had been in decline throughout the 1980s.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] By 1987, the three local Corio District football leagues – the GFL, GDFL and BFL – were held in higher regard within Geelong than the Association was, meaning that local clubs attracted larger crowds and better sponsorship and could offer higher player payments than Geelong West.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Additionally, many Geelong-based players preferred to play a Saturday afternoon game locally, rather than play a Sunday afternoon game and be required to travel to Melbourne every second week.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Geelong West's minor grades had been suffering the consequences of this for many years – the thirds in particular had been routinely thrashed by more than 300 points since the early 1980s – but by 1987 the senior team was also suffering.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] After six weeks, the club was sitting winless in last place, was struggling to draw crowds and was in a poor financial position.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] On Friday 29 May, the Geelong West playing group forfeited its Round 7 games in all three grades, seeking to make a highly public gesture to call attention to the club's ailing viability and lack of players.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] It was also speculated and reported that the players were striking over $15,000 in match payments collectively owed to the group at the time; it was confirmed that this money was owing, but the players denied this was the motivation for the forfeiture.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The players had reportedly been planning the boycott for about a month before enacting it.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The following week, a public appeal began to raise money for and encourage local players to play for the club, using the club's position as one of the city's most historically successful local clubs over a period of more than 100 years to gain support.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] On 10 June, the Association intervened: it gave the club until 30 June to prove that it was financially viable and could reliably field teams in all three grades, or it would face suspension for the rest of the year; and, the club was provisionally suspended until it could prove those two things.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Geelong West drew with second-placed Frankston in its first game back to gain its first points for the year, but it went on to win only one more game and was relegated at the end of the year.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The club lasted one more season in the Association, before withdrawing after the 1988 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] In the final round of the home-and-away season, Sunshine was scheduled to play Caulfield in the Association's first ever Friday night game at the newly upgraded Skinner Reserve.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Caulfield responded that it would not play the game unless the Association guaranteed that it would not apply a retroactive suspension; the Association did not give this assurance, so Caulfield forfeited the game, and was fined $1,500 as a result.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Sunshine, which was angry with Caulfield after having invested money promoting the game, staged a match between the firsts and Seconds on the Friday night instead.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Caulfield never played another Association game, as it was later suspended for the 1988 season, which ultimately ended the club's time in the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Division 1 home-and-away season was played over eighteen rounds; the top four then contested the finals under the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The finals were played at the Junction Oval.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Clubs who won on forfeit were awarded a win and four premiership points, credited with the round's average winning score as 'points for', and debited the round's average losing score as 'points against'.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The ladder as it is shown here distinguishes wins by forfeiture from wins in completed matches, but not all sources make this distinction.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Division 2 home-and-away season was played over eighteen rounds; the top four then contested the finals under the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The finals were played at Junction Oval.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] In 1987, the Association competed in and won the NFL Shield, the NFL's interstate competition among the minor states.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] It was the first time the Association had contested an NFL-sanctioned interstate event since its expulsion from the ANFC/NFL in 1970; the Association held a competition membership, but not a full membership, of the NFL at this time.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] Terry Wheeler (Williamstown) was coach of the team; Jeff Sarau (Frankston) was the captain, with Barry Round (Williamstown) stepping up in Sarau's absence against Queensland.
[src:skinner-reserve/1987-vfa-season] The Grand final against Tasmania was delayed for 35 minutes, because heavy fog prevented the Tasmanian team's flight from landing in Melbourne.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The **1988 VFA season** was the 107th season of the top division of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), and the 28th and final season of second division competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Division 1 premiership was won by the Coburg Football Club, after it defeated Williamstown in the Grand Final on 18 September by 27 points; it was Coburg's fifth Division 1 premiership.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The final Division 2 premiership was won by Oakleigh; it was the club's second Division 2 premiership, and the last premiership ever won by the club in either division.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Association contracted substantially in 1988.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Additionally, Moorabbin, which had been suspended in May 1987 for the remainder of that season, did not seek re-admission for 1988.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The controversial FORT review from December 1986 was considered instrumental in shaping the clubs' departures.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Even though the Association never received a mandate to enforce the FORT recommendations, all five of the clubs who departed saw the FORT review as partly responsible for their demise.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Caulfield, which had been relegated from Division 1 at the end of 1981, had struggled to remain competitive in Division 2.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Its financial viability had been borderline throughout its time in Division 2, and the club occasionally struggled to field minor grade teams.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club was also not helped by a clubroom fire in 1985.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club fell behind on its Association levies in July and August 1987, resulting in its suspension from the final match of the 1987 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] By November, the club still owed the Association $11,000 in levies and fines, and on 4 November, the Association executive suspended Caulfield for the 1988 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club did not dispute that it was behind on its levies, but believed that the Association suspended it, rather than showing lenience, because of its desire to achieve the FORT's vision of a rationalised competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club never returned to the Association, ending its 80-year affiliation which had begun in Brighton in 1908 before moving to Caulfield in 1962.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club merged with the Ashburton Football Club and played in the South East Suburban Football League in 1988.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club never returned, ending its 80-year affiliation with the Association, and soon disbanded.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] At its annual general meeting on 12 November 1987, Berwick discussed whether or not to withdraw from the Association and return to the South West Gippsland Football League.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club had not enjoyed any significant improvement in local support and its financial position had suffered since joining the Association from the SWGFL in 1983; and, there were concerns after the FORT review that Division 2 had an uncertain future.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The motion to leave the Association was passed by a narrow majority at the meeting, and Berwick returned to the SWGFL in 1988, ending its five-year affiliation with the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club also noted that it was faced with paying a $5,000 instalment of its affiliation levy in November, with Caulfield's suspension sending a clear message that the club faced suspension if it failed to pay.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Some at the club believed this to be a cynical ploy by the Association to drive its weaker clubs out of the competition, further raising concerns about whether it could survive long-term in the competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] As of 2021, the club remains active, most recently in the Eastern Football League.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] In early March 1988, Waverley announced that it was in financial trouble.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] It had not paid its players for 1987, nor had it paid its most recent $5,000 instalment of the affiliation levy, it was $58,000 in debt and it needed to raise $20,000 within two weeks to remain in operation.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club expected to be suspended if failed to pay its levies, but had no other way of raising the necessary cash, so it ceased operations and folded on 11 March, ending its 28-year affiliation with the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] After Round 4, Mordialloc met to decide whether to stay in the Association or not.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club was performing very poorly on the field, having lost its three games by a combined 428 points – it struggled to recruit quality players, which it blamed on its proximity to the more successful Sandringham and Frankston and the uncertainty generated by the FORT review.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Additionally, the immediate future of Division 2 was looking weaker than ever, as Brook Andersen had predicted to the media in late March that he expected the Association to have reduced to 14 teams in one division by 1989.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The club was not in any immediate financial trouble, but it was concerned that a full year of continued uncompetitive performances in the uncertain Division 2 environment could cause financial trouble which would force the club to fold.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] As such, on 5 May, the club opted to withdraw immediately from the Association, ending an affiliation which had lasted just over thirty years.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The following week, the club began playing in the South East Suburban Football League, where it believed it had greater long-term viability; and as of 2021, it is indeed still competing in the league's successor, the Southern Football League.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] In March, one of the FORT review's key recommendations was formally endorsed when the structure of the Association's Board of Management was changed; now, instead of being composed of delegates representing each of the clubs, a six-man independent board was elected at the beginning of the year.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The change brought an end to the club-based administrative model under which the Association had operated for 111 years since its establishment in 1877.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The finals were played at the North Port Oval and the Grand Final was played at Windy Hill.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Division 2 fixture was originally drawn up with eight teams over eighteen rounds, including both Waverley and Mordialloc.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Following Waverley's departure, the fixture was unchanged except that Waverley's opponent was scheduled for a bye each week.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] After Mordialloc's departure, the Association expunged Mordialloc's three games from the record entirely; the rest of the season's fixture was re-drawn to ensure each team played a total of eighteen games.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The top four of the six remaining teams then contested the finals under the Page–McIntyre system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The semi-finals and preliminary final were played at the home ground of the higher-ranked team in the match; the Grand Final was played at Windy Hill.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Association competed in the second division of the 1988 Adelaide Bicentennial Carnival, held from 2 March to 5 March.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The carnival was played under state of origin rules, so the Association was given permission to play up to five players from the VFL, SANFL or WAFL who began their senior careers in the Association, in addition to any currently-listed Association players regardless of their origin.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] It was the first time the Association had played representative games under origin rules.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Barry Round (Williamstown) captained the Association team.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Association finished in second place after being defeated by Northern Territory in the Grand Final.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Terry Wallace (Richmond, formerly of Camberwell) won the Dolphin Medal as the best player in Division 2 during the carnival, and he was the sole Association player selected in the All-Australian team.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Association then played two stand-alone interstate games, both under non-origin rules.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The first was against Tasmania in Hobart.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The second was against the West Australian Football League in Perth, and was played as a curtain-raiser to a state-of-origin match between Western Australia (which was composed of VFL and WAFL players of Western Australian origin) and Victoria.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The VFA team also played a match against the Victorian Amateur Football Association on the evening of Wednesday 1 June at Skinner Reserve.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] This was not an official representative match, as both associations treated it as a practice match for their other representative fixtures.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The VFA won the practice match by three goals.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] It was the first time the Association had received weekly television coverage since 1981.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The central ground arrangement was not popular with all clubs: Sandringham complained after its 16 April match against Brunswick that it lost $8,000 in takings as a result of playing its home game in front of 500 spectators at Port Melbourne, when it could have attracted 5,000 at Beach Oval.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] This arrangement extended to the first three weeks of the Division 1 finals, which were all played on Saturdays at North Port Oval after many years of having been played on Sundays at Junction Oval.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Division 1 Grand Final was also televised, but the deal with the ABC allowed the game to be played on Sunday, and did not require it to be played at Port Melbourne.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Association initially confirmed that Junction Oval would continue to serve as the Grand Final venue, but these plans were abandoned in July when the venue's ageing grandstands were declared a fire hazard by the MFB.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Over the following six weeks, the Association negotiated with a number of councils to find a new Grand Final venue.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Its first choice venue was Princes Park, and while it had the support of ground management, approval could not be gained from the Melbourne City Council to play on Sunday.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Its second choice, Victoria Park, was likewise unable to gain approval for Sunday football from the Collingwood Council.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The ground management at Western Oval, Footscray, was willing and able to host the entire finals series including a Sunday Grand Final, but the ABC television deal required the first three finals to be played at Port Melbourne, and Footscray was unwilling to host just the Grand Final.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Eventually, on 19 August, the Association confirmed Windy Hill as the Grand Final venue, with the support of both the ground management and the Essendon Council for Sunday football.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Division 2 Grand Final continued to be played as a curtain-raiser to the Division 1 Grand Final, but the other three Division 2 finals matches were played as stand-alone games on Sundays.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Rather than secure a central venue, these matches were played at the home ground of the higher-placed team.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Other novel scheduling options were trialled to overcome the fact that the VFL was now playing nine Sunday home-and-away matches in Victoria during the season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] In the lead-up to the Association's representative match against the WAFL on Tuesday 5 July, the Association announced that players in the representative team would be ineligible to play in their clubs' premiership matches on the weekend of 2–3 July.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] In an act of defiance, Preston fielded Shaw anyway; he kicked eight goals, and Preston defeated eventual minor premiers Coburg by 16 points; Preston 19.8 (122) d.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The Association decided not to suspend Shaw himself, but awarded the game to Coburg and fined Preston $500.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Preston took the Association to court, seeking to have the original result of the game reinstated; and, in a decision handed down in the week before the finals, the courts found in Preston's favour and reinstated the win.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] Also considered was the double standard that Tony Pastore, who was not in the Association team but travelled to Perth as an emergency, had been allowed to play for Williamstown on the 2–3 July weekend.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] The finding was damaging to the credibility of the Association's new independent Board of Management.
[src:skinner-reserve/1988-vfa-season] As a result of the court's decision, Preston moved from third to second on the ladder, relegating Williamstown from second to third, and forcing the Seagulls to play in the first semi-final three days later.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-90-national-soccer-league] The **1989–90 National Soccer League** season, was the 14th season of the National Soccer League in Australia.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-90-national-soccer-league] The league was known as the **Quit NSL** under a sponsorship arrangement with the Victorian Health Promotion Foundation.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-90-national-soccer-league] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) goal difference; 3) number of goals scored.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The **1989 VFA season** was the 108th season of the Victorian Football Association (VFA), an Australian rules football competition played in the state of Victoria.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The season began on 9 April and concluded on 24 September, comprising an 18-match home-and-away season over 20 rounds, followed by a four-week finals series.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Coburg won the premiership for the second year in a row and the sixth time overall, defeating Williamstown by 20 points in the 1989 VFA Grand Final.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] As of 2025, it is the last time Coburg has won a senior VFA/VFL premiership.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] This was the first season since 1960 in which the VFA operated as a single-division competition, having operated as a two-division competition with promotion and relegation for the previous 28 years.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] After several years of speculation, the Association's second division was dissolved for the 1989 season and competition was re-combined into a single division, ending 28 years of partitioned competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Talk of the imminent demise of Division 2 began following the folding of Waverley in March 1988, at which point the size of the Association had reduced to 17 teams; Mordialloc's withdrawal a month later reduced the size to sixteen.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] By the end of the year, president Brook Andersen confirmed that the 1989 season would operate as a single division; and, that while his preference was for a twelve- or fourteen-team competition, all sixteen teams would be given the opportunity to justify their positions in the competition.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The only club to withdraw between the end of 1988 and the beginning of 1989 was Geelong West.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The club decided that it needed to return to the local competition, where operating costs were lower, and where it would attract stronger support by performing at a more competitive level, and it formally withdrew from the Association on 27 October.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The club was not permitted to join the GFL in its own right due to its proximity to the existing St Peters Football Club, but St Peters saw its own long-term viability as uncertain, so was willing to enter a merger.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The resultant club was known as the Geelong West St Peters Football Club.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Consequently, the size of the Association was reduced to fifteen teams, the smallest since 1957.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] With fifteen clubs in one division, the Association introduced the McIntyre final five system to replace the Page–McIntyre final four system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The top two from the 1988 home-and-away season, Oakleigh and Werribee, were reasonably competitive, finishing with records of 8–10; but the other three clubs, Dandenong, Camberwell and Sunshine, were completely uncompetitive, and quickly risked causing embarrassment to the Association.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The step up from Division 2 to the combined division was too great for it to manage, and after eight games, it was winless with a percentage of 31, and had twice conceded scores in excess of 300 points.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] On 8 June, Sunshine announced its withdrawal from the seniors and reserves competitions for the rest of the season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] It intended to use the remainder of the season to regroup, secure local sponsorships, and target strong Footscray District Football League players and fringe Footscray Football Club League players to recruit a competitive playing list for the 1990 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The club granted unconditional clearances to its players, hoping they would return to the club in 1990; and it continued to field an Under-19s team for the rest of the season, against the protests of some teams.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The eight games Sunshine had played were expunged from the records, and the rest of the senior and reserves fixture was redrawn to give all teams an equal number of games.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] At the end of the year, Sunshine was confident that it had rebuilt itself to be a viable and competitive club; but the Association disagreed and terminated its licence permanently at the end of the season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Camberwell and Dandenong were a little more competitive than Sunshine.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Dandenong's sole win for the season came against Camberwell, and it conceded 200 points six times during the year.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] In the home-and-away season, each team played eighteen games over 20 rounds.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The fixture after Round 9 was redrawn following the withdrawal of Sunshine from the senior and reserves competition (the under-19s fixture was unchanged).
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The top five then contested the finals under the McIntyre final five system.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] The primary finals venue was North Port Oval, and the grand final was played at Windy Hill.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Numbers highlighted in green indicate that the team finished the round inside the top 5.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Numbers highlighted in blue indicates the team finished first on the ladder in that round.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Numbers highlighted in red indicates the team finished in last place on the ladder in that round.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Grey indicates that the team had withdrawn from the season.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] numbers indicate that the team had a bye during that round.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] In 1989, the Association competed in and won the NFL Shield, the NFL's interstate competition among the minor states, held in Tasmania over the Queen's Birthday weekend.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Phil Cleary (Coburg) was coach of the Association team, and Brett McTaggart (Williamstown) was captain.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Because Tasmania unexpectedly finished last in the qualifying matches, attendances and takings at later matches dropped, resulting in all six competing states losing $40,000 in expenses over the event.
[src:skinner-reserve/1989-vfa-season] Rino Pretto (Oakleigh) kicked a VFA representative record of twelve goals in the grand final.
[src:skinner-reserve/1990-91-national-soccer-league] The **1990–91 National Soccer League** season, was the 15th season of the National Soccer League in Australia.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Prior to Skinner Reserve being developed as a football ground, the primary sports venue in the City of Sunshine was Selwyn Park in Albion.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] In 1964, the local council agreed to lease Selwyn Park to George Cross FC, which was playing in Victoria's top-level soccer league at the time.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] However, the Sunshine Football Club (SFC), as well as local baseball and sub-district cricket clubs, still had three years to run on their lease at the venue.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] To secure agreement from the SFC to end the lease, the Sunshine City Council committed to developing a new VFA-standard venue at Skinner Reserve.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The venue was built during the 1965 season, with the football club signing a seven-year lease that begun in 1966.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Before construction was finished, the Footscray Football Club – which was competing in the Victorian Football League (VFL) – made an application to the council to permanently move its playing and administrative base from Western Oval to the new venue and develop it into a VFL-standard ground.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] At the time, fellow VFL clubs St Kilda and North Melbourne had recently moved their bases to VFA venues (Moorabbin Oval and Coburg City Oval respectively).
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The council ultimately honoured its existing agreement with the Sunshine Football Club and rejected Footscray's application.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The ground was named after Henry Robert Skinner, who served as the mayor of Sunshine for one term in 1952.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Sunshine played its first VFA match at Skinner Reserve on 23 April 1966, losing to Prahran by four points.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The venue had a very wide playing surface, high grassed embankments for spectators, and a grandstand – narrow, but quite tall by suburban standards – named the **J.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Chigwidden Stand**, after long-serving club secretary Jack Chigwidden.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] In addition to Sunshine's home matches, Skinner Reserve hosted VFA seconds/reserves finals matches, including several grand finals.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] VFL clubs often pre-season matches at the ground because it was not used for cricket during much of its history, rendering it available during summer.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Floodlights were installed at the ground in 1987 to enable matches to be played at night, although the only such VFA premiership match to be scheduled was cancelled due to the forfeiture of Sunshine's opponent, Caulfield, for unrelated reasons.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Sunshine competed in Division 2 for most of its time in the VFA.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Because of this, crowd numbers at Skinner Reserve were lower than other clubs and often did not exceed 1,000.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The venue had a capacity of around 15,000 people at the time, although it was never recorded reaching that number.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The VFA dissolved Division 2 at the end of the 1988 season.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Sunshine was part of the single-division competition in 1989, but it was uncompetitive against the VFA's strongest sides and withdrew from the competition on 8 June 1989.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Its final match at Skinner Reserve was a 146-point loss to Springvale in round 7, although Coburg played Port Melbourne at the venue in round 18 after wet weather turned Coburg City Oval into a mudheap.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] On 22 October 1989, a fundraising match was held between former Footscray and Collingwood players at Skinner Reserve, which drew a large crowd of 8,000 people as part of a campaign to stop a proposed merger between Footscray and Fitzroy.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] George Cross FC (known as Sunshine George Cross FC by this point) played National Soccer League (NSL) matches at Skinner Reserve, beginning in November 1989.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] A crowd of 6,100 people watched the club's first match at the ground, which saw George Cross defeat South Melbourne FC 2–0.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] During the 1990–91 season, two matches at Skinner Reserve saw crowds of 4,000 people.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] After George Cross returned to the Victoria Premier League in 1992, the club moved to Chaplin Reserve in Sunshine.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The Chigwidden Stand was demolished in late 2015.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Its function as a pavilion was taken over by the Braybrook Community Hub, which is located in the wider Braybrook Park area.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] In February 2016, the ground's cricket pitch was dug up and vandalised overnight between the first and second day of a Victorian Turf Cricket Association (VTCA) match between Kingsville Baptist and Sunshine Heights.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The damage rendered the wicket unplayable and the match was declared abandoned, meaning Kingsville missed out on qualification for the finals.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Redevelopment of Skinner Reserve began in October 2021, which was co-funded by the Western Bulldogs and the Maribyrnong City Council.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The Bulldogs used the ground for training in 2022 while Whitten Oval was undergoing renovation.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The redevelopment was completed in February 2023, providing the venue with new floodlights and a running track around the perimeter of the oval.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Maribyrnong Greens SC, which moved to Skinner Reserve in the 2000s, criticised the Bulldogs after it was forced to change its training schedule.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] The Western Football Netball League (WFNL) hosted the Thirds grand final – along with Division 1 men's, senior women's and under-18s finals matches – at Skinner Reserve in 2024.
[src:skinner-reserve/skinner-reserve] Several WFNL home-and-away matches have also been held at the venue since the redevelopment was completed.
